('cs-prem-0011-ards-vent','nclex','case_study','ards_mechanical_ventilation','ARDS — low tidal volume',4,
'The intubated client on volume-control ventilation has a plateau pressure of 34 cm H2O and a tidal volume set at 9 mL/kg predicted body weight. PaO2/FiO2 is 140. Which ventilator change should the nurse anticipate?',
'ARDS — lung-protective ventilation',
'A client with severe pneumonia progressed to ARDS. Current settings: Vt 9 mL/kg PBW, PEEP 8, FiO2 0.8. ABG shows refractory hypoxemia.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Reduce tidal volume toward 6 mL/kg predicted body weight"},{"id":"b","text":"Increase tidal volume to improve minute ventilation"},{"id":"c","text":"Disconnect PEEP to lower the plateau pressure"},{"id":"d","text":"Switch to pressure support and allow spontaneous breathing"}]',
'a',
'ARDS requires lung-protective ventilation: tidal volumes of 6 mL/kg predicted body weight and plateau pressures <= 30 cm H2O to prevent ventilator-induced lung injury. A plateau of 34 with Vt 9 mL/kg is injurious and should be reduced.',
'ARDS is diffuse alveolar injury producing non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema, poor compliance, and refractory hypoxemia (PaO2/FiO2 <= 300; this client at 140 is moderate-severe). The landmark ARDSNet evidence established that lung-protective ventilation reduces mortality: tidal volume 6 mL/kg of PREDICTED body weight (not actual weight) and plateau pressure kept <= 30 cm H2O to avoid volutrauma/barotrauma of the few remaining aerated alveoli (the "baby lung"). This client''s Vt of 9 mL/kg with a plateau of 34 is actively injurious, so the priority change is to lower the tidal volume toward 6 mL/kg and accept permissive hypercapnia. Raising the tidal volume worsens injury; removing PEEP collapses recruited alveoli and worsens hypoxemia (PEEP is therapeutic in ARDS); switching to spontaneous pressure support is premature in refractory hypoxemia. Pearl: in ARDS, 6 mL/kg PBW and plateau <= 30 — small breaths save lungs.',
'{"b":"Larger tidal volumes increase volutrauma and mortality in ARDS; the goal is smaller breaths.","c":"PEEP recruits collapsed alveoli and improves oxygenation in ARDS; removing it worsens hypoxemia.","d":"Spontaneous pressure-support breathing is premature during refractory hypoxemia with high plateau pressures."}',
'[{"title":"ARDSNet / ATS-ESICM-SCCM ARDS Guidelines","citation":"Low tidal volume 6 mL/kg PBW, plateau <= 30 cm H2O reduces mortality."}]',
'["case_study","respiratory","ARDS","ventilation","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0012-aki-contrast','nclex','case_study','acute_kidney_injury','AKI — nephrotoxin avoidance',3,
'A client with a creatinine of 2.1 mg/dL and reduced eGFR is scheduled for a contrast-enhanced CT. Which order should the nurse question?',
'Contrast-associated AKI risk',
'The client has diabetes and CKD stage 3. Home medications include metformin, lisinopril, and ibuprofen PRN. The provider has written pre-procedure orders.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Continue metformin on the morning of the contrast study"},{"id":"b","text":"Administer IV isotonic fluids before and after contrast"},{"id":"c","text":"Use the lowest effective volume of contrast"},{"id":"d","text":"Recheck renal function after the procedure"}]',
'a',
'Metformin should be held around iodinated contrast in clients with reduced renal function because contrast-associated AKI can impair metformin clearance and precipitate lactic acidosis. Hydration, minimal contrast, and post-procedure monitoring are appropriate.',
'This client is at high risk for contrast-associated acute kidney injury: pre-existing CKD stage 3 (creatinine 2.1, reduced eGFR) plus diabetes. The order to question is continuing metformin: although metformin does not cause AKI itself, if contrast precipitates AKI the kidneys can no longer clear metformin, and accumulation can cause life-threatening lactic acidosis. Guidelines advise holding metformin at the time of contrast in patients with eGFR below ~30-60 and resuming only after renal function is confirmed stable ~48 hours later. The other orders are protective and correct: IV isotonic fluid before and after is the best-evidence prevention for contrast nephropathy, minimizing contrast volume reduces nephrotoxic load, and rechecking creatinine detects injury early. NSAIDs (the PRN ibuprofen) would also ideally be held. Pearl: around iodinated contrast in renal impairment — hydrate, minimize contrast, and hold metformin.',
'{"b":"IV isotonic hydration is the best-evidence prevention for contrast nephropathy and is appropriate.","c":"Minimizing contrast volume reduces nephrotoxic load and is correct.","d":"Post-procedure renal monitoring detects AKI early and is appropriate."}',
'[{"title":"ACR Manual on Contrast Media / KDIGO","citation":"Hold metformin around contrast with reduced eGFR; isotonic hydration for prevention."}]',
'["case_study","renal","AKI","pharmacology","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0013-abruption','nclex','case_study','placental_abruption','Placental abruption — recognition',4,
'A 34-week pregnant client reports sudden, severe, constant abdominal pain with dark vaginal bleeding. The uterus is rigid and tender, and the fetal heart rate shows late decelerations. Which is the nurse''s priority action?',
'Third-trimester bleeding emergency',
'Vital signs: BP 138/86 then 96/58 over 20 minutes, HR rising to 116. The client has a history of hypertension and tobacco use.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Notify the provider emergently, position the client left-lateral, give oxygen and IV fluids, and prepare for possible emergent cesarean"},{"id":"b","text":"Perform a vaginal exam to assess cervical dilation"},{"id":"c","text":"Reassure the client and continue routine monitoring"},{"id":"d","text":"Encourage ambulation to promote labor progress"}]',
'a',
'The picture is placental abruption — a maternal-fetal emergency. The priority is emergent escalation with maternal stabilization (left-lateral position, oxygen, IV access/fluids) and preparation for emergent cesarean while monitoring for hemorrhagic shock and DIC.',
'Placental abruption is premature separation of the placenta, presenting classically with sudden constant (not intermittent) abdominal pain, dark vaginal bleeding, a rigid/board-like tender uterus, and non-reassuring fetal status such as late decelerations. This client''s risk factors (chronic hypertension, tobacco use) and her falling blood pressure with rising heart rate signal evolving hemorrhagic shock — and the concealed bleeding behind the placenta means visible blood underestimates true loss. The priority is immediate escalation with simultaneous maternal stabilization: left-lateral positioning to relieve aortocaval compression and improve placental perfusion, high-flow oxygen, large-bore IV access with fluids, continuous fetal monitoring, type and crossmatch, and preparation for emergent cesarean. A vaginal exam is contraindicated in third-trimester bleeding until placenta previa is excluded (it can provoke catastrophic hemorrhage), and reassurance or ambulation dangerously delays care. Pearl: painful dark bleeding with a rigid uterus = abruption; painless bright bleeding = previa (no vaginal exam in either until previa is ruled out).',
'{"b":"Vaginal exams are contraindicated in third-trimester bleeding until placenta previa is excluded; they can cause catastrophic hemorrhage.","c":"This is an obstetric emergency with fetal compromise and maternal instability — routine monitoring is unsafe.","d":"Ambulation is dangerous during active abruption with maternal instability and fetal compromise."}',
'[{"title":"ACOG — Placental Abruption","citation":"Recognition and emergent management of abruptio placentae; avoid vaginal exam until previa excluded."}]',
'["case_study","OB","abruption","emergency","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0014-peds-dehydration','nclex','case_study','pediatric_dehydration','Pediatric severe dehydration',3,
'A 10-month-old with 3 days of vomiting and diarrhea has sunken eyes, a sunken fontanelle, capillary refill of 4 seconds, lethargy, and no wet diaper in 8 hours. Which is the nurse''s priority intervention?',
'Infant dehydration — shock risk',
'Weight is down 9% from baseline. HR 178, peripheral pulses weak. The child is minimally responsive to stimulation.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Establish IV/IO access and give a 20 mL/kg isotonic fluid bolus"},{"id":"b","text":"Offer oral rehydration solution by mouth in small sips"},{"id":"c","text":"Weigh the child again in 4 hours and reassess"},{"id":"d","text":"Administer an antiemetic and observe"}]',
'a',
'This infant has severe dehydration with signs of hypovolemic shock (≈9% weight loss, delayed capillary refill, tachycardia, weak pulses, lethargy). The priority is rapid IV/IO isotonic fluid resuscitation with a 20 mL/kg bolus, repeated as needed.',
'Infants decompensate quickly because their higher body-water turnover and limited reserve make fluid losses proportionally larger. The findings here — roughly 9% weight loss, sunken eyes and fontanelle, capillary refill of 4 seconds, weak pulses, tachycardia (HR 178), and lethargy — indicate SEVERE dehydration with early hypovolemic shock. The priority is rapid volume restoration: establish IV access, or intraosseous access if IV cannot be obtained quickly in a decompensating infant, and give a 20 mL/kg bolus of isotonic crystalloid (normal saline or LR), reassessing and repeating up to 60 mL/kg while monitoring perfusion. Oral rehydration is appropriate only for mild-to-moderate dehydration in an alert child who can drink — it is unsafe and too slow for a lethargic infant in shock. Delaying for a repeat weight or giving an antiemetic without restoring perfusion ignores a life threat. Pearl: severe pediatric dehydration with shock signs = immediate IV/IO 20 mL/kg isotonic bolus, not oral fluids.',
'{"b":"Oral rehydration is for mild-moderate dehydration in an alert child; a lethargic infant in shock needs IV/IO fluids.","c":"Delaying for a repeat weight ignores active hypovolemic shock requiring immediate resuscitation.","d":"An antiemetic does not restore perfusion; volume resuscitation is the priority."}',
'[{"title":"AAP / WHO Dehydration Management","citation":"Severe dehydration: 20 mL/kg isotonic IV/IO bolus, reassess and repeat."}]',
'["case_study","pediatric","dehydration","shock","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0015-thyroid-storm','nclex','case_study','thyroid_storm','Thyroid storm recognition',4,
'A client with Graves disease presents with temperature 40.1 C, HR 156 atrial fibrillation, agitation, and vomiting after a recent infection. Which clinical interpretation should guide the nurse''s response?',
'Hyperthyroid crisis',
'The client recently ran out of methimazole. The client is diaphoretic, tremulous, and increasingly confused.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Thyroid storm requiring emergent temperature control, beta blockade, and antithyroid therapy"},{"id":"b","text":"Simple febrile illness that will resolve with antipyretics"},{"id":"c","text":"Anxiety attack triggered by the recent infection"},{"id":"d","text":"Expected Graves symptoms needing only routine follow-up"}]',
'a',
'Hyperthermia, severe tachyarrhythmia, agitation/altered mentation, and GI symptoms in a client with Graves disease and a precipitant (infection, stopped antithyroid drug) define thyroid storm — a life-threatening emergency requiring aggressive cooling, beta blockade, and antithyroid therapy.',
'Thyroid storm is decompensated, life-threatening thyrotoxicosis, often triggered by infection, surgery, or abrupt cessation of antithyroid medication (this client stopped methimazole). The diagnostic cluster is hyperpyrexia (40+ C), severe tachyarrhythmia (here atrial fibrillation at 156), CNS dysfunction (agitation progressing to confusion), and GI symptoms — captured by the Burch-Wartofsky scoring system. Mortality is high without rapid treatment. Management is multi-pronged and time-critical: beta blockers (propranolol) to control the dangerous adrenergic cardiac effects, a thionamide (propylthiouracil or methimazole) to block new hormone synthesis, iodine given AFTER the thionamide to block hormone release, corticosteroids to reduce peripheral T4-to-T3 conversion, and aggressive cooling plus treatment of the precipitating infection. Mistaking this for simple fever, anxiety, or routine Graves symptoms delays life-saving therapy. Pearl: fever + AFib + altered mental status in a hyperthyroid patient who stopped their meds = thyroid storm; treat emergently.',
'{"b":"A temperature of 40 C with tachyarrhythmia and altered mentation in Graves disease is not a simple febrile illness — it is a thyrotoxic crisis.","c":"Anxiety does not cause hyperpyrexia or atrial fibrillation; this is a metabolic emergency.","d":"These are decompensated crisis findings, not expected stable Graves symptoms; routine follow-up is unsafe."}',
'[{"title":"American Thyroid Association — Thyrotoxicosis","citation":"Thyroid storm management: beta blockade, thionamide, iodine after thionamide, steroids, cooling."}]',
'["case_study","endocrine","thyroid_storm","emergency","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch()),

('cs-prem-0016-tension-pneumo','nclex','case_study','tension_pneumothorax','Tension pneumothorax',4,
'A client with blunt chest trauma develops sudden severe dyspnea, absent breath sounds on the right, tracheal deviation to the left, distended neck veins, and BP 78/40. Which intervention should the nurse anticipate first?',
'Chest trauma — obstructive shock',
'The client is acutely hypoxic and anxious. SpO2 has fallen to 84% despite high-flow oxygen.',
'[{"id":"a","text":"Emergent needle decompression of the right chest followed by chest tube insertion"},{"id":"b","text":"Obtain a chest X-ray to confirm before any intervention"},{"id":"c","text":"Place the client supine and administer a sedative"},{"id":"d","text":"Increase oxygen and continue to monitor"}]',
'a',
'Absent unilateral breath sounds with tracheal deviation away from the affected side, distended neck veins, and hypotension is tension pneumothorax — a clinical diagnosis requiring immediate needle decompression, not delayed imaging.',
'Tension pneumothorax occurs when air enters the pleural space through a one-way leak and cannot escape, progressively collapsing the lung and shifting mediastinal structures. The shift kinks the great vessels and reduces venous return, producing obstructive shock. The hallmark findings here are diagnostic: sudden severe dyspnea with absent breath sounds on the affected (right) side, tracheal deviation AWAY from that side (to the left), distended neck veins from impaired venous return, hypotension, and refractory hypoxia. This is a CLINICAL diagnosis — waiting for a chest X-ray to confirm can be fatal. The immediate intervention is emergent needle decompression (large-bore needle, traditionally 2nd intercostal space midclavicular line, or 5th intercostal space anterior axillary line) to convert the tension to a simple pneumothorax, followed by definitive chest tube placement. Lying the patient flat and sedating, or simply increasing oxygen, ignores the obstructive shock. Pearl: tension pneumothorax is diagnosed at the bedside and decompressed immediately — never delay for imaging.',
'{"b":"Tension pneumothorax is a clinical diagnosis; waiting for confirmatory imaging can be fatal.","c":"Supine positioning and sedation do not relieve the tension and can worsen respiratory status.","d":"Oxygen alone cannot overcome the mechanical obstruction; decompression is required now."}',
'[{"title":"ATLS / Trauma Guidelines","citation":"Tension pneumothorax: immediate needle decompression then chest tube; clinical diagnosis."}]',
'["case_study","respiratory","trauma","emergency","NGN","premium"]','published','final-curated-live',unixepoch(),unixepoch());
